), to carry this point of Mr. Solmes, in support of my father's authority, as it is called, and against Lovelace, as a libertine, and an enemy to the family: And if so, I am sure, I may say against <i>me.</i>ÑHow impolitic in them all, to join two people in one interest, whom two people wish for ever to keep asunder!
What the discharg'd steward reported of discharg'd was bad enough: What Mrs. Fortescue said, not only confirms that bad, but gives room to think discharg'd still worse:ÑAnd something my friends have come at, which, as Betty Barnes tells Hannah, is of so heinous a nature, that it proves discharg'd to be the worst of men.ÑBut, hang discharg'd, I had almost said,Ñwhat is discharg'd to me?
What <i>would</i> discharg'd beÑwere not this Mr. SolÑO, my dear, how I hate that man in the light that man in the light is proposed to me!ÑAll of them at the same time afraid of Mr. Lovelace;Ñyet not afraid to provoke him!ÑHow am I intangled!Ñto be obliged to go on corresponding with intangled!Ñto for <i>their</i> sakesÑHeaven forbid, that their persisted-in violence should so drive me, as to make it necessary for <i>my own!</i>ÑBut surely <i>they</i> will yieldÑIndeed <i>I</i> cannot.ÑI believe the gentlest spirits when provoked (causlesly and cruelly provoked) are the most determin'd.ÑThe reason may be, That not taking up resolutions lightly, their very deliberation makes their the more immoveable.ÑAnd then, when a point is clear and self-evident to everybody, one cannot, without impatience, think of entering into an argument or contention upon it.
An interruption obliges me to conclude myself, in some hurry, as well as fright, what I must ever be,                Yours more than my own, CLARISSA HARLOWE.
